               <p><span class="addition">It follows, as a corollary from this, that </span><br> <span class="addition">external Nature also imitates Art. The only </span><br> <span class="addition">effects that she can show us are effects</span> <br> <span class="addition">that we have already seen through </span><br> <span class="addition">poetry, or in paintings. This is the secret of </span><br> <span class="addition">Nature's charm, as well as the </span><br> <span class="addition">explanation of Nature's weakness. </span><br></p>
               					
               <p>The <span class="deletion">last doctrine </span><span class="addition">final revelation </span>is that Lying, the<br> telling of beautiful untrue 
                  <milestone n="nc_56" unit="page_number"></milestone>things, is the<br> proper aim of Art.<note rend="small">149</note> But of this I<br> think I have spoken at sufficient length.<br> And now let us go out on the <span class="deletion">T</span><span class="addition">t</span>errace, <br>where <span class="addition"><span class="deletion">"</span></span><span class="addition"><span class="deletion">'</span></span><span class="addition">"</span><span class="addition">droops </span>the milk-white peacock <span class="deletion">glimmers </span><br>like a ghost,<span class="addition"><span class="deletion">"</span></span><span class="addition"><span class="deletion">'</span></span><span class="addition">"</span> <span class="deletion">and </span><span class="addition">while </span>the evening star <span class="addition"><span class="deletion">"</span></span><span class="addition"><span class="deletion">'</span></span><span class="addition">"</span>washes <br>the dusk with silver.<span class="addition"><span class="deletion">"</span></span><span class="addition"><span class="deletion">'</span></span><span class="addition">"</span><note rend="small">150</note>At twilight<br> <span class="deletion">N</span><span class="addition">n</span>ature becomes a wonderfully suggestive effect<span class="addition">,</span><br> and is not without loveliness, though <br>perhaps <span class="deletion">her </span><span class="addition">its </span>chief use is to <span class="deletion">supply </span><br><span class="deletion">illustrations for </span><span class="addition">illustrate </span>quotations from the<br> poets. Come<span class="addition">!</span><span class="deletion">.</span> We have talked long <br>enough.<br></p>
               				
