               or “return to” an all-encompassing Absolute connection to “Nature,” creating a singular
               “objective” experience. These positions are not mutually exclusive, and indeed many
               scholars have read pantheism and Romantic conceptions of nature as an subsumption
               of individuality by the impersonal. Relatedly, Hilda Schiff’s influential reading
               of the essay argues that Wilde offers a conception of the artist-nature relationship
               in which, in deference to nature as the ideal, nature not only fails to “unite” with
