            <p>Germane to Wilde’s Paterian influence and discussion of imitation, Poe invoked Carlyle
               in a short piece appearing in the January 22, 1845 issue of the Evening Mirror entitled,
               “American Diffuseness—Objectionable Concision.” After lamenting the “diffuseness of
               the American Legislative oratory,” Poe pivots his attention to the literary and “the
               species of concision which has been lately introduced among us, through imitation
               of that prophet in great and quack in little matters, Carlyle.” Prefiguring Pater’s
               understanding of “Style,” Poe argues that contrary to the goal of concision being
               “to save time... in saving thought... That style, therefore, is the most truly concise
               which most rapidly transmits the sense” (Edgar Allan Poe, “American Diffuseness —
               Objectionable Concision,” Evening Mirror, New York, vol. I, no. 91, January 22, 1845,
               p. 2, col. 2).
            </p>
            				
            <p>In the posthumously published “About Critics and Criticism,” he writes: “The manner
