               with himself and Carlyle. The style of Miss Fuller is conventional — with herself
               and Emerson and Carlyle: — that is to say, it is a triple-distilled conventionality:
               — and by the word “conventionality,” as here used, I mean very nearly what, as regards
               personal conduct, we style “affectation” — that is, an assumption of airs or tricks
               which have no basis in reason or common sense.”
