            <p>135. Quote from William Morris’s 1887 translation of The Odyssey of Homer, which Wilde
               reviewed for the Paul Mall Gazette in April and Nov. 1887 (Guy 406-407). Of the deletion,
               Schroeder writes: “In Guy's opinion, the original Nineteenth Century version 'may
               be a reference to Samuel Henry Butcher, a fellow of Trinity College, Cambridge, who
               published a popular translation of the Odyssey in 1879' (in collaboration with Andrew
               Lang). But this does not make sense, as Butcher / Lang do not use the word 'whopper'”
               (58).
            </p>
            				
            <p>The shift from an incredulous “whopper” to “sly” deceit furthers the suggestion that
               “lying” with a purpose of deception or conscious craft, as distinct from “self-conscious”
               creation/invention, are two distinct acts in Wilde’s aesthetic theory (as put forth
               here).
            </p>
            				
            <p>136. The agent behind the change from “rose” to “grew”—with all its natural/organic
               implication—is undocumented. The revisions of “young” to “mankind” addition of “important”
               while replacing “whole” further down (around the “question”), all amplify the stakes
               of the discourse.
            </p>
            				
            <p>137. An allusion to Quod Nihil Sictur [That Nothing is Known], by Jesuit scholar,
               Francisco Sanchez (Guy 407).
            </p>
            				
            <p>138. As Guy summarizes: “district School Boards were the product of the 1870 Education
               Act which made elementary schooling compulsory for children aged 5-12. In order to
               meet this provision, the existing structure of private and church schools had to be
               supplemented by a network of new state-sponsored institutions funded directly from
               taxation. These new schools were administered by a directly elected Board which had
               the power to levy a local education rate to run the school and to compel attendance”
               (408). See also Barnard, H. C. A Short History of English Education from 1760 to 1944.
               Univ. of London Press, 1947.
            </p>
            				
            <p>The removal of “moral” expands the range of “improvement” implied (intellectual, professional,
               moral, etc.)
            </p>
            				
            <p>139. Center of London Newspaper industry. For Wilde’s critique of journalism, see
               "Pen, Pencil, and Poison” in which Wilde, writing of Thomas Griggiths Wainewright,
               humorously writes that it’s a tragedy that his most successful and “influen[tial]”
               writing was his journalistic style: “To have a style so gorgeous that it conceals
               the subject is one of the highest achievements of an important and much admired school
               of Fleet Street leader-writers, and this school Janus Weathercock may be said to have
               invented. . .A publicist, now-a-days, is a man who bores the community with the details
               of the illegalities of his private life” (114-115). Later, discussing Wainewright’s
               exile, the punishment for his crimes, jokingly laments, “there is, however, something
               dramatic in the fact that this heavy punishment was inflicted for, what, if we remember
               his fatal influence on the prose of modern journalism, was certainly not the worst
               of all his sins” (118-119).
            </p>
            				
            <p>140. This cut sentence makes the case more explicitly, as Hilda Schiff argues, that
               Wilde construed “lying” as an absolute “freedom” from the structuring of our subjective
               experience by culture, which becomes apparent in mimetic efforts. In turn, lying is
               thus an assertion of individuality.
            </p>
            				
            <p>141. For more on Wilde’s careful delineation between types of “lying,” See note 135
               paragraph 2.
            </p>
            				
            <p>142. As Schroeder reports: “The 'solid stolid British intellect' seems to have been
               a popular cliché in late Victorian times. In his Essays on Poetry and Poets, a collection
               which Wilde reviewed in Dec. 1886 , Roden Noel (1834-94), for example, speaks of 'the
               stolid, practical, but rather obtuse English mind.' And for Lady Wilde, not surprisingly,
               stolidness seems to have been likewise the dominant English character trait, if we
               can believe the Athenaeum reviewer of her volume on Ancient Cures, Charms, and Usages
               of Ireland who took great pains to quote all the passages where the word 'stolid'
               occurred and who cried out at the end in protest” (58).
            </p>
            				
            <p>143. Moved up from position after "land." in Berg</p>
            				
            <p>144. "golden" in Berg; See similar revision series on Folio 28. Wilde's revision here
               seems to reinforce the privileging of ostensible appearances, artifice, and presentation
               over some "real" "essence" or objective "truth"
            </p>
            				
            <p>145. A revision that suggests Pater’s Renaissance and his writing was synonymous with
               the Aesthetic movement.
            </p>
            				
            <p>146. As Josephine Guy writes, “The idea that late Greak art received forms and techniques
               from an earlier period had been suggested by Walte Pater in his essay ‘The Beginnings
               of Greek Sculpture’. . .Pater argued that the work of Phidias expressed certain qualities
               anticipated in the work of Homer” (409).
            </p>
            				
            <p>Schroeder notes, Wilde’s assertion here was re-articulated in his “review 'Mr William
               Morris's Last Book' (March 1889): 'From an artistic point of view it [Morris's Tale
               of the House of the Wolfings] may be described as an attempt to return by a self-conscious
               effort to the conditions of an earlier and a fresher age. Attempts of this kind are
               not uncommon in the history of art. From some such feeling came the Pre-Raphaelite
               movement of our own day and the archaistic movement of later Greek sculpture.'” (59).
            </p>
            				
            <p>Guy also notes that “Wilde is referring to the influence of the original Pre-Raphaelite
               Brotherhood, founded in 1848, on a later generation of artists and poets, such as
               Burne-Jones, Swinburne, William Morris, and of course Wilde himself” (410).
            </p>
            				
            <p>147. Revisions shift the sentence from an implication of perspective to act “commit[ted]”</p>
            				
            <p>148. This final sentence suggests that, for Wilde, to mimic is to be behind, to lie
               is to create, and to influence culture through the creation of art is to augment the
               cultural frameworks which structure our future perceptions and encounters with the
               world. And in this way, art becomes anticipatory of life and provides “form” for the
               “expression of Life,” as signaled in the paragraph below and expanded upon in the
               below addition, beginning with “it follows,” to the 1891 edition. See also Wilde’s
               differentiation between the redeemable “lying for its own sake” and other forms of
               non-artistic/creative lying.
            </p>
            				
            <p>149. As Schroeder notes: “things, is the proper aim of Art. Vivian's 'final revelation'
               served as the climax in Punch's little rhymed satire 'In Defence of the Great Paradoxist'
               (May 1892): 'He may not be "earnest," he may not be "smart," / You may say, if you
               please, he's unable to sing; / But, oh, you must own he's a "work of art," - / A "beautiful
               untrue thing!"'”
            </p>
            				
            <p>150. Allusions to Tennyson’s The Prncess and William Blake’s “To the Evening Star.”
               And, as Schroeder observes, “The two quotations recall Swinburne's essay on Blake
               (1866) - the essay, it will be remembered, gave Wilde the title for 'Pen, Pencil and
               Poison' in which Swinburne singled out the line from Blake's ode 'To the Evening Star'
               for particular praise and put it side by side with the poetry of Tennyson” (59).
            </p>
            				
